<Layout title="Comparing Manetho's king lists">
	<section class="page-content">
		<div class="lead pt-3 sizep-95">
			More than two millenia has passed since <a href="/authors">Manetho</a> wrote his <em>Aegyptiaca</em> in Egypt. The transmission of the original manuscript
			has not been easy, nor is it wholly trustworthy.
		</div>

		<p class="pt-3">
			As the lists are straightforward, tabulating them together is easy. Discrepancies naturally occur, from errors in copying, misreading the
			original, to intentional changes, basically any of a multitude of human errors.<br /><br />
			<a href="/authors/africanus">Africanus</a> is generally considered more trustworthy than <a href="/authors/eusebius">Eusebius</a>, because his
			edition is more complete and was written a hundred years prior to Eusebius, and might have been less 'tainted' by earlier versions of the
			Epitome closer to the original text of Manetho.
		</p>

